body: I suspect this will be fixed by https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/271, but in case not I'm filing here. I'm not even sure the banner is needed, but it shows up and then the buttons don't actually do what you want.

comment_data.body:
Right.  There are (at least) two issues:
1. the pub banner shows even though we've run pub behind the scenes in `flutter create` --- maybe @alexander-doroshko can chime in on what we might do here...
2. `pub get` doesn't do the right thing for Flutter w/o some massaging --- as you note, this is fixed with #271 and will work as soon as a new Dart plugin is pushed

Thanks!

1. Banner is shown if there's no `.packages` file near `pubspec.yaml` or if `.packages` file is older than pubspec.
2. I guess you want me to cherry-pick that fix to 162 branch and update the Dart plugin?

> Banner is shown if there's no .packages file near pubspec.yaml or if .packages file is older than pubspec.

Ah.  That makes sense.  

> I guess you want me to cherry-pick that fix to 162 branch and update the Dart plugin?

If possible that would be awesome!

_(Edited my previous comment for correctness.)_

@eseidelGoogle : could you confirm that there's a `.packages` file next to your pubspec and that it's indeed newer?

@pq I'm not sure what you're asking for?  This is the list from the project I filed this from, but it's been run, etc. since so I'm sure the timestamps are no longer useful to you.  You can just follow the "create a project" flow in intellij to test yourself.

Thanks @eseidelGoogle.  This is actually what I was asking for.  I did the flow locally, had similar timestamps but did _not_ see the broken pub banner (but have in the past).  Investigating further...

Yes, it looks like a race. Refresh may not help as file may be open in editor when .packages is not created yet. To avoid race after Dart project creation we have `DartPubActionBase.isInProgress()` check but it doesn't work for Flutter. Need to think more.
Great.  Thanks for giving this thought!
@alexander-doroshko : curious if you have any more thoughts on this one?

See `com.jetbrains.lang.dart.ide.inspections.DartOutdatedDependenciesInspection#checkFile` and `com.jetbrains.lang.dart.ide.actions.DartPubActionBase#isInProgress`. Without changes at Dart plugin side I see no way to skip showing `'Pub get' has not been run` while `flutter create` is in progress.

Exactly.  I was thinking this would require some changes in the Dart plugin as well.  I'm curious how you think this would be easiest.  Could we simply disable this test in the case of Flutter modules?  (And defer to Flutter to ensure that pub gets properly run?)
Moving to 0.1.7, I hit this again several times today as mentioned in #508
CC @pq would be good to get this one moving.

Thanks for the nudge @mit-mit !

I've got a PR out to update the Dart plugin as @alexander-doroshko suggests: https://github.com/JetBrains/intellij-plugins/pull/452 but as I look at calling this method from the Flutter side I recall that @devoncarew mentioned some classloader issues I may want to consider?

I was planning to do simple reflection like:

    DartPubActionBase.class.getMethod("setIsInProgress");

but now I'm thinking this will just pull in the class defined in the Dart jar (and not the loaded plugin).  Is that right?

/cc @devoncarew @alexander-doroshko

There are no class loader issues with using public classes/methods.
You can't make cross-plugin package-local calls because package-local things are not visible from a different class loader.
No reflection please :)

> No reflection please :)

I was hoping to use reflection so that I could write code that would work with the current plugin and just get better when a new Dart Plugin is available.  (This is such a small feature I didn't think it justified bumping our minimum requirement on the Dart version.)  Not hugely invested either way.

My question was probably a misunderstanding though. I realize now that at runtime we're probably not loading classes from the Dart plugin jars in the Flutter plugin and that those are just there for development.  Or maybe I'm even more confused.  (Very possible without coffee! ☕️ )
We've landed the fix for this in the Dart plugin (we'll then need to make corresponding fixes in the Flutter plugin).
(we need to patch the fix to the dart plugin into the current stable release)
Confirmed that the Dart plugin fixes are *not* in the latest plugin so this is blocked until the next push.

Looks like this didn't make it into `163.10154.19` either but should be in the next one.

**EDIT**: looks like we're targeting `2016.3.2`.
